    what_changed: 'On 2 July 2012, Australia introduced the Mineral Resource Rent Tax (MRRT), a 22.5% tax on super-profits from mining projects—profits above a 12% return on invested capital.\n\nBefore this, mining companies paid only standard company tax (30%) and state-based royalties. After the MRRT, major mining operations faced a new federal layer taxing extraordinary profits from finite resources.\n\nThe government hoped to collect $3-5 billion annually. The policy was controversial: mining companies including BHP Billiton and Rio Tinto had negotiated directly with Prime Minister Julia Gillard before the tax was finalized. Smaller miners like Fortescue Metals were excluded from those negotiations, creating the perception that the big three miners had secured a less-onerous tax than smaller competitors would have faced.',
