    impact_score: 8,
    confidence_score: 0.88,
    what_changed: 'On 9 January 2023, amid an energy crisis, the Labor government announced an emergency gas price cap of AUD $12 per gigajoule (GJ) for domestic supply.\n\nBefore this cap, wholesale gas prices had spiked to AUD $40+ per GJ in mid-2022 following Russia\'s invasion of Ukraine and global LNG market tightening.\n\nElectricity generators and manufacturers faced unsustainable costs. After the cap, gas producers (Santos, Woodside, Shell, Chevron) could not sell domestic gas above $12/GJ, forcing them to choose: accept lower domestic prices or redirect LNG cargo to export markets at higher world prices. The cap was intended to last 12 months and reduce wholesale electricity costs by enabling cheaper gas-powered electricity generation. Gas producers fiercely opposed the cap, warning it would reduce investment in future gas projects. Simultaneously, the government announced the Capacity Investment Scheme (AUD $10 billion underwriting) to accelerate renewable energy deployment.',
